vectorData.altText: 4. Click on the star that corresponds to the level at which a lumbar puncture is typically performed.
That's right!  A lumbar puncture is typically performed between the L3 and L4 vertebrae.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The lumbar cistern is an expansion of the subarachnoid space, and thus, in life, contains CSF.
Identify the other contents of the lumbar cistern, the cauda equina      and filum terminale interna.
The cauda equina consists of lumbar and sacral spinal rootlets descending to their points of exit from the subarachnoid space and vertebral canal.
IDENTIFY the location of the lumbar cistern     :
it is within the dural sac, extending from the conus medullaris, at the level of the L2 vertebra, to the end of the dural sac, at the level of the S2 vertebral body.
site of a lumbar puncture, a procedure in which CSF is withdrawn via a needle
inserted between the L3 and L4 vertebrae.
